article.headline: Stephens scores 26 for 'Horns
article.linkText: Texas beats Kansas for fifth straight time
article.story:
LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) -- Even at less than full strength, Stacy
Stephens was too much for Kansas to handle.

Texas' senior forward, still rehabbing from surgery in June on
her left Achilles' tendon, had a season-high 26 points in
third-ranked Texas' 73-54 victory over the Jayhawks in the Big 12
opener for both Wednesday night.

"Every day out, every game out, I feel a little bit better,"
Stephens said. "The doctor said six to nine months and I'll be
back at 100 percent. I'm still not 100, but I'm getting there."

Heather Schreiber hit three 3s and added 18 points, and Tiffany
Jackson had 16 points for Texas (13-1), which extended its winning
streak to six games and beat the Jayhawks (7-5) for the fifth
straight time.

Stephens, Schreiber and Jackson also had nine rebounds each for
the Longhorns, who controlled the boards 40-24.

"We knew if we gave them second and third shots, it was going
to be a long night," Schreiber said. "We were focused on keeping
them off the boards and getting second-chance shots for our team."

Kansas trailed by 14 points at halftime but cut the margin to
44-38 on Kandis Bonner's 3-point play with just over 15{ minutes
remaining.

Stephens drew two fouls on Bonner over the next 90 seconds,
though, and the Longhorns scored on both possessions to start a
16-4 run that gave them a 60-42 lead with just over seven minutes
left.

"This was a Stacy Stephens-type game, and we haven't really
seen that prior to this game," Texas coach Jody Conradt said.
"She's still coming back from the surgery, and her conditioning
isn't what it would be normally at this time of year. So it's
really good to see her step up -- and at a really opportune time."

After that run by the Longhorns, Kansas could get no closer than
14 points.

"Kansas is a much-improved team," Conradt said. "They're
going to beat some people in the Big 12. I'm just thankful it
wasn't Texas tonight."

Jackson, held to two points in the first half, scored eight in
Texas' decisive surge and six more down the stretch.

"The defense was really collapsing on me the first half,"
Jackson said. "The second half, the guards just put me in good
positions and gave me good passes."

Tamara Ransburg, who hit her first six shots and finished
8-for-10 from the field, led Kansas with 16 points. Crystal Kemp
was 6-for-9 and added 12 points.

The rest of the Jayhawks shot a combined 11-for-37 (30 percent),
while Texas shot 49 percent (31-for-63).

Ransburg's basket with 8:33 left in the first half got Kansas to
22-18, but the Jayhawks didn't score again until Ransburg hit from
the lane with 3:19 remaining.

"I think we got a little too excited at times," Kemp said.
"We have to be able to take the momentum, and we didn't do that."

Schreiber scored four points in Texas' 10-0 run over that span,
and Stephens had six points in the last 2{ minutes to put Texas up
38-24 at the half.
